    {
      "id": 19,
      "documentId": "rpftbhear1a3guib3bll19u8",
      "title": "From Farm to Export: The Journey of Dried Managu",
      "slug": "from-farm-to-export-the-journey-of-dried-managu",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Dried managu (African nightshade) is one of the most popular products in AgroDakk's catalog — and for good reason. This leafy green vegetable is packed with iron, calcium, and vitamins A and C. But how does it get from a small farm in Kitale to a dinner plate in Berlin or Dubai?",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "The journey begins with our partner farmers, who grow managu using traditional methods enhanced with modern sustainable practices. The leaves are harvested by hand at peak ripeness — typically early in the morning when nutrient content is highest.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Within hours of harvesting, the managu arrives at our processing facility in Kitale. Here, it undergoes thorough washing, sorting, and quality inspection. Only the best leaves make the cut.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "The drying process is crucial. We use natural sun-drying methods that preserve the vegetable's nutritional profile while extending its shelf life to over 12 months. After drying, the product is tested for quality, packaged in food-grade materials, and prepared for shipment.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "publishedDate": "2026-03-11",
      "excerpt": "Tracing the supply chain of one of Kenya's most nutritious indigenous vegetables — from small farms in Kitale to international dinner tables.",
      "author": "Peter Ochieng",
      "featured": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-06-14T12:33:43.844Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-06-28T08:53:24.402Z",
