    {
      "id": 15,
      "documentId": "fgxkf8gfq8uhj3zb6bxxwast",
      "title": "Why African Indigenous Vegetables Are the Next Superfood",
      "slug": "why-african-indigenous-vegetables-are-the-next-superfood",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Move over kale and quinoa — African indigenous vegetables are emerging as the next big thing in global nutrition. Vegetables like managu, saga (spider plant), and kunde (cowpea leaves) have been staples in East African diets for generations, and now the rest of the world is catching on.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "These vegetables are nutritional powerhouses. Managu contains up to 4 times the iron of spinach. Saga is rich in calcium, making it excellent for bone health. Kunde provides high levels of plant-based protein — up to 25% by dry weight.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "International nutritionists and food scientists are increasingly studying these vegetables for their potential to address malnutrition in both developing and developed countries. The UN Food and Agriculture Organization has identified several African indigenous vegetables as \"crops of the future.\"",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "For health-conscious consumers in Europe and North America, dried versions of these vegetables offer a convenient way to incorporate superfoods into their daily diets.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "publishedDate": "2026-01-20",
      "excerpt": "Rich in iron, calcium, and vitamins, vegetables like managu, saga, and kunde are gaining recognition in global nutrition circles.",
      "author": "\tDr. Amina Hassan",
      "featured": false,
      "createdAt": "2026-06-14T12:34:44.778Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-06-28T08:50:50.903Z",
